my repository kubid/obelus_tech,\\
I&#x27;ve added an ssh-key.. I put my .pub key on the repository setting.

in my server when I try to pull it return:

{code}
repository access denied. deployment key is not associated with the requested repository.
{code}

when I check using ssh -v git@bitbucket.org, it return:

{code}
This deploy key has read access to the following repositories:
kubid/obelus_tech: ssh_key_name -- deploy@xxxx
{code}

how  do I change it into read/write access ?

In the online editor, all code after a template literal is highlighted as a comment.

It properly terminates, when viewing the file outside the editor.

Example:

{code}
#!javascript

if (value < 0 || value > 100) {
  console.warn(`Warning: ${value}`); // Everything after the last back-tick is highlighted as a comment
}

if (value <= 0) {
  this.die();
}

{code}

Getting this error on pull requests and branches that are being updated, and also on the activity tab for those pull requests

{code}
#!python

Error
We were unable to load this page.
{code}

When trying to access the [/2.0/addon/linkers|https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/addon/linkers] resource using [the {{request}} function defined by Bitbucket&#x27;s Javascript API|https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/javascript/module-request.html] from the [configuration page of an addon|https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/modules/configurePage.html] I get the folowing result with a 404 response code:

{{{code: "request_failed", message: "Request failed"}}}

Example code:

{code:js}
AP.require(&#x27;request&#x27;, function(request){
  request({
    url: &#x27;/2.0/addon/linkers&#x27;,
    success: function(responseText){
      console.log(responseText);
    },
    error: function(responseText){
      console.log(responseText);
    }
  });
});
{code}

However, the documentation on the request function states that the XMLHttpRequest is executed "in the context of the host application", so I assume it should have access to all Bitbucket resources the addon / user has access to, and this should include the addon&#x27;s own linkers.

When doing a request to the /2.0/addon/linkers resource using a JWT token generated for the addon I do get a valid response.

I have been running a maven build locally using the guide provided [here|https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/debug-your-pipelines-locally-with-docker-838273569.html]. The build works perfectly in a local environment but fails (mostly) on bitbucket due to OOM. I see following error in the logs:

{code}
#!bash

[ERROR] Failed to execute goal org.codehaus.mojo:exec-maven-plugin:1.6.0:exec (mvn-package-for-python-test) on project demo-python: Command execution failed. Process exited with an error: 137 (Exit value: 137) -> [Help 1]

{code}

With error code 137 showing that the process was killed forcefully.  Is there any other resource constraint that the provided [guide|https://confluence.atlassian.com/bitbucket/debug-your-pipelines-locally-with-docker-838273569.html] is missing or the 4G memory support isn&#x27;t really 4G?

It would be nice to have the possibility to have the project-name instead the team-name in the repo-url.

Then:

{code}
https://bitbucket.org/projectname/reponame
{code}

and not

{code}
https://bitbucket.org/teamname/reponame
{code}

To allow backward compatibilty, the users should have the possibility to choose which kind of url they want to have.

Furthermore for team developing more applications, it is often the case to have same repo names in differents project, e.g. "api", "models",... are names and repos used in differents projects.

Originally asked here: https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Bitbucket-questions/How-to-include-project-in-repo-path-not-just-team-name/qaq-p/592843#M17799
